# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-loss-prevention-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] An **Internet filter** is a type of Internet censorship that restricts or controls the content an Internet user is capable to access, especially when utilized to restrict material delivered over the Internet via the Web, Email, or other means.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The motive is often to prevent access to content which the computer's owner(s) or other authorities may consider objectionable.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] When imposed without the consent of the user, content control can be characterised as a form of internet censorship.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some filter software includes time control functions that empowers parents to set the amount of time that child may spend accessing the Internet or playing games or other computer activities.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The term "content control" is used on occasion by CNN, *Playboy* magazine, the *San Francisco Chronicle*, and *The New York Times*.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] However, several other terms, including "content filtering software", "web content filter", "filtering proxy servers", "secure web gateways", "censorware", "content security and control", "web filtering software", "content-censoring software", and "content-blocking software", are often used.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] "Nannyware" has also been used in both product marketing and by the media.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Industry research company Gartner uses **"secure web gateway"** (SWG) to describe the market segment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some products log all sites that a user accesses and rates them based on content type for reporting to an "accountability partner" of the person's choosing, and the term accountability software is used.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Internet filters, parental control software, and/or accountability software may also be combined into one product.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Those critical of such software, however, use the term "censorware" freely: consider the Censorware Project, for example.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Filters can be implemented in many different ways: by software on a personal computer, via network infrastructure such as proxy servers, DNS servers, or firewalls that provide Internet access.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] No solution provides complete coverage, so most companies deploy a mix of technologies to achieve the proper content control in line with their policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] E-mail filters act on information contained in the mail body, in the mail headers such as sender and subject, and e-mail attachments to classify, accept, or reject messages.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] , a type of statistical filter, are commonly used.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Both client and server based filters are available.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This type of filter is installed as software on each computer where filtering is required.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This filter can typically be managed, disabled or uninstalled by anyone who has administrator-level privileges on the system.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Content-limited (or filtered) ISPs are Internet service providers that offer access to only a set portion of Internet content on an opt-in or a mandatory basis.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Anyone who subscribes to this type of service is subject to restrictions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] functionality to filter outbound as well as inbound information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] All users are subject to the access policy defined by the institution.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The filtering can be customized, so a school district's high school library can have a different filtering profile than the district's junior high school library.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This type of filtering is implemented at the DNS layer and attempts to prevent lookups for domains that do not fit within a set of policies (either parental control or company rules).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] offer filtering options as part of their services.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] can be also be used for this purpose, though client-side only.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] offer users the option of turning on a safety filter.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] When this safety filter is activated, it filters out the inappropriate links from all of the search results.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] If users know the actual URL of a website that features explicit or adult content, they have the ability to access that content without using a search engine.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some providers offer child-oriented versions of their engines that permit only child friendly websites.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some offer security software which includes parental controls.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] operating system also includes content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Internet does not intrinsically provide content blocking, and therefore there is much content on the Internet that is considered unsuitable for children, given that much content is given certifications as suitable for adults only, e.g.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Internet service providers (ISPs) that block material containing pornography, or controversial religious, political, or news-related content en route are often utilized by parents who do not permit their children to access content not conforming to their personal beliefs.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Content filtering software can, however, also be used to block malware and other content that is or contains hostile, intrusive, or annoying material including adware, spam, computer viruses, worms, trojan horses, and spyware.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Most content control software is marketed to organizations or parents.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] It is, however, also marketed on occasion to facilitate self-censorship, for example by people struggling with addictions to online pornography, gambling, chat rooms, etc.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Self-censorship software may also be utilised by some in order to avoid viewing content they consider immoral, inappropriate, or simply distracting.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] A number of accountability software products are marketed as *self-censorship* or *accountability software*.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] These are often promoted by religious media and at religious gatherings.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Content filtering technology exists in two major forms: application gateway or packet inspection.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] For HTTP access the application gateway is called a web-proxy or just a proxy.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Such web-proxies can inspect both the initial request and the returned web page using arbitrarily complex rules and will not return any part of the page to the requester until a decision is made.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In addition they can make substitutions in whole or for any part of the returned result.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Packet inspection filters do not initially interfere with the connection to the server but inspect the data in the connection as it goes past, at some point the filter may decide that the connection is to be filtered and it will then disconnect it by injecting a TCP-Reset or similar faked packet.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The two techniques can be used together with the packet filter monitoring a link until it sees an HTTP connection starting to an IP address that has content that needs filtering.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The packet filter then redirects the connection to the web-proxy which can perform detailed filtering on the website without having to pass through all unfiltered connections.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This combination is quite popular because it can significantly reduce the cost of the system.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] There are constraints to IP level packet-filtering, as it may result in rendering all web content associated with a particular IP address inaccessible.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This may result in the unintentional blocking of legitimate sites that share the same IP address or domain.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] For instance, university websites commonly employ multiple domains under one IP address.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Moreover, IP level packet-filtering can be surpassed by using a distinct IP address for certain content while still being linked to the same domain or server.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Gateway-based content control software may be more difficult to bypass than desktop software as the user does not have physical access to the filtering device.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] However, many of the techniques in the Bypassing filters section still work.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Content labeling may be considered another form of content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In 1994, the Internet Content Rating Association (ICRA) — now part of the Family Online Safety Institute — developed a content rating system for online content providers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Using an online questionnaire a webmaster describes the nature of their web content.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] A small file is generated that contains a condensed, computer readable digest of this description that can then be used by content filtering software to block or allow that site.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] ICRA labels come in a variety of formats.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] These include the World Wide Web Consortium's Resource Description Framework (RDF) as well as Platform for Internet Content Selection (PICS) labels used by Microsoft's Internet Explorer Content Advisor.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] ICRA labels are an example of self-labeling.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Similarly, in 2006 the Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection (ASACP) initiated the Restricted to Adults self-labeling initiative.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] ASACP members were concerned that various forms of legislation being proposed in the United States were going to have the effect of forcing adult companies to label their content.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The RTA label, unlike ICRA labels, does not require a webmaster to fill out a questionnaire or sign up to use.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Both labels are recognized by a wide variety of content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Voluntary Content Rating (VCR) system was devised by Solid Oak Software for their CYBERsitter filtering software, as an alternative to the PICS system, which some critics deemed too complex.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] It employs HTML metadata tags embedded within web page documents to specify the type of content contained in the document.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Only two levels are specified, *mature* and *adult*, making the specification extremely simple.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Australian Internet Safety Advisory Body has information about "practical advice on Internet safety, parental control and filters for the protection of children, students and families" that also includes public libraries.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] NetAlert, the software made available free of charge by the Australian government, was allegedly cracked by a 16-year-old student, Tom Wood, less than a week after its release in August 2007.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Wood supposedly bypassed the $84 million filter in about half an hour to highlight problems with the government's approach to Internet content filtering.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Australian Government has introduced legislation that requires ISPs to "restrict access to age restricted content (commercial MA15+ content and R18+ content) either hosted in Australia or provided from Australia" that was due to commence from 20 January 2008, known as Cleanfeed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a proposed mandatory ISP level content filtration system.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] It was proposed by the Beazley led Australian Labor Party opposition in a 2006 press release, with the intention of protecting children who were vulnerable due to claimed parental computer illiteracy.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] It was announced on 31 December 2007 as a policy to be implemented by the Rudd ALP government, and initial tests in Tasmania have produced a 2008 report.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is funded in the current budget, and is moving towards an Expression of Interest for live testing with ISPs in 2008.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Public opposition and criticism have emerged, led by the EFA and gaining irregular mainstream media attention, with a majority of Australians reportedly "strongly against" its implementation.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Criticisms include its expense, inaccuracy (it will be impossible to ensure only illegal sites are blocked) and the fact that it will be compulsory, which can be seen as an intrusion on free speech rights.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Another major criticism point has been that although the filter is claimed to stop certain materials, the underground rings dealing in such materials will not be affected.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The filter might also provide a false sense of security for parents, who might supervise children less while using the Internet, achieving the exact opposite effect.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a responsibility of Senator Conroy's portfolio.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In Denmark it is stated policy that it will "prevent inappropriate Internet sites from being accessed from children's libraries across Denmark".
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] "'It is important that every library in the country has the opportunity to protect children against pornographic material when they are using library computers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Many libraries in the UK such as the British Library and local authority public libraries apply filters to Internet access.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] According to research conducted by the Radical Librarians Collective, at least 98% of public libraries apply filters; including categories such as "LGBT interest", "abortion" and "questionable".
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The use of Internet filters or content-control software varies widely in public libraries in the United States, since Internet use policies are established by the local library board.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Many libraries adopted Internet filters after Congress conditioned the receipt of universal service discounts on the use of Internet filters through the Children's Internet Protection Act (CIPA).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Other libraries do not install content control software, believing that acceptable use policies and educational efforts address the issue of children accessing age-inappropriate content while preserving adult users' right to freely access information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some libraries use Internet filters on computers used by children only.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Many legal scholars believe that a number of legal cases, in particular *Reno v.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] American Civil Liberties Union*, established that the use of content-control software in libraries is a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Children's Internet Protection Act [CIPA] and the June 2003 case *United States v.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The plurality decision left open a future "as-applied" Constitutional challenge, however.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In November 2006, a lawsuit was filed against the North Central Regional Library District (NCRL) in Washington State for its policy of refusing to disable restrictions upon requests of adult patrons, but CIPA was not challenged in that matter.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Court said: "It appears to us that NCRL's filtering policy is reasonable and accords with its mission and these policies and is viewpoint neutral.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] It appears that no article I, section 5 content-based violation exists in this case.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] NCRL's essential mission is to promote reading and lifelong learning.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] As NCRL maintains, it is reasonable to impose restrictions on Internet access in order to maintain an environment that is conducive to study and contemplative thought." The case returned to federal court.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In March 2007, Virginia passed a law similar to CIPA that requires public libraries receiving state funds to use content-control software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Like CIPA, the law requires libraries to disable filters for an adult library user when requested to do so by the user.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Utilizing a filter that is overly zealous at filtering content, or mislabels content not intended to be censored can result in over-blocking, or over-censoring.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Overblocking can filter out material that should be acceptable under the filtering policy in effect, for example health related information may unintentionally be filtered along with porn-related material because of the Scunthorpe problem.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Filter administrators may prefer to err on the side of caution by accepting over blocking to prevent any risk of access to sites that they determine to be undesirable.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Content-control software was mentioned as blocking access to Beaver College before its name change to Arcadia University.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Another example was the filtering of Horniman Museum.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] As well, over-blocking may encourage users to bypass the filter entirely.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Whenever new information is uploaded to the Internet, filters can under block, or under-censor, content if the parties responsible for maintaining the filters do not update them quickly and accurately, and a blacklisting rather than a whitelisting filtering policy is in place.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Many would not be satisfied with government filtering viewpoints on moral or political issues, agreeing that this could become support for propaganda.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Many would also find it unacceptable that an ISP, whether by law or by the ISP's own choice, should deploy such software without allowing the users to disable the filtering for their own connections.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In the United States, the First Amendment to the United States Constitution has been cited in calls to criminalise forced internet censorship.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Many types of content-control software have been shown to block sites based on the religious and political leanings of the company owners.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Examples include blocking several religious sites (including the Web site of the Vatican), many political sites, and homosexuality-related sites.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] *X-Stop* was shown to block sites such as the Quaker web site, the National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law, The Heritage Foundation, and parts of The Ethical Spectacle.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] CYBERsitter blocks out sites like National Organization for Women.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Nancy Willard, an academic researcher and attorney, pointed out that many U.S. public schools and libraries use the same filtering software that many Christian organizations use.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In 1998, a United States federal district court in Virginia ruled (Loudoun v.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Board of Trustees of the Loudoun County Library) that the imposition of mandatory filtering in a public library violates the First Amendment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In 1996 the US Congress passed the Communications Decency Act, banning indecency on the Internet.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Civil liberties groups challenged the law under the First Amendment, and in 1997 the Supreme Court ruled in their favor.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Part of the civil liberties argument, especially from groups like the Electronic Frontier Foundation, was that parents who wanted to block sites could use their own content-filtering software, making government involvement unnecessary.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] In the late 1990s, groups such as the Censorware Project began reverse-engineering the content-control software and decrypting the blacklists to determine what kind of sites the software blocked.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This led to legal action alleging violation of the "Cyber Patrol" license agreement.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] They discovered that such tools routinely blocked unobjectionable sites while also failing to block intended targets.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some content-control software companies responded by claiming that their filtering criteria were backed by intensive manual checking.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The companies' opponents argued, on the other hand, that performing the necessary checking would require resources greater than the companies possessed and that therefore their claims were not valid.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] The Motion Picture Association successfully obtained a UK ruling enforcing ISPs to use content-control software to prevent copyright infringement by their subscribers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Content filtering in general can "be bypassed entirely by tech-savvy individuals." Blocking content on a device "[will not]…guarantee that users won't eventually be able to find a way around the filter." Content providers may change URLs or IP addresses to circumvent filtering.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Individuals with technical expertise may use a different method by employing multiple domains or URLs that direct to a shared IP address where restricted content is present.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] This strategy doesn't circumvent IP packet filtering, however can evade DNS poisoning and web proxies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Additionally, perpetrators may use mirrored websites that avoid filters.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some software may be bypassed successfully by using alternative protocols such as FTP or telnet or HTTPS, conducting searches in a different language, using a proxy server or a circumventor such as Psiphon.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Also cached web pages returned by Google or other searches could bypass some controls as well.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Web syndication services may provide alternate paths for content.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Some of the more poorly designed programs can be shut down by killing their processes: for example, in Microsoft Windows through the Windows Task Manager, or in Mac OS X using Force Quit or Activity Monitor.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Numerous workarounds and counters to workarounds from content-control software creators exist.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Google services are often blocked by filters, but these may most often be bypassed by using *https://* in place of *http://* since content filtering software is not able to interpret content under secure connections (in this case SSL).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] An encrypted VPN can be used as means of bypassing content control software, especially if the content control software is installed on an Internet gateway or firewall.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/content-control-software] Other ways to bypass a content control filter include translation sites and establishing a remote connection with an uncensored device.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] In some data exfiltration scenarios, a large amount of aggregated data may be exfiltrated.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] However, in these and other scenarios, it is likely that certain types of data may be targeted.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Several techniques have been used by malicious actors to carry out data exfiltration.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] The technique chosen depends on a number of factors.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] If the attacker has or can easily gain physical or privileged remote access to the server containing the data they wish to exfiltrate, their chances of success are much better than otherwise.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] For example, it would be relatively easy for a system administrator to plant, and in turn, execute malware that transmits data to an external command and control server without getting caught.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Similarly, if one can gain physical administrative access, they can potentially steal the server holding the target data, or more realistically, transfer data from the server to a DVD or USB flash drive.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] In many cases, malicious actors cannot gain physical access to the physical systems holding target data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] In these situations, they may compromise user accounts on remote access applications using manufacturer default or weak passwords.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] In 2009, after analyzing 200 data exfiltration attacks that took place in 24 countries, SpiderLabs discovered a ninety percent success rate in compromising user accounts on remote access applications without requiring brute-force attacks.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Once a malicious actor gains this level of access, they may transfer target data elsewhere.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Additionally, there are more sophisticated forms of data exfiltration.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Various techniques can be used to conceal detection by network defenses.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] For example, Cross Site Scripting (XSS) can be used to exploit vulnerabilities in web applications to provide a malicious actor with sensitive data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] A timing channel can also be used to send data a few packets at a time at specified intervals in a way that is even more difficult for network defenses to detect and prevent.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] A number of things can be done to help defend a network against data exfiltration.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] One example of detective measures is to implement intrusion detection and prevention systems and regularly monitor network services to ensure that only known acceptable services are running at any given time.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] If suspicious network services are running, investigate and take the appropriate measures immediately.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Preventive measures include the implementation and maintenance of access controls, deception techniques, and encryption of data in process, in transit, and at rest.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-exfiltration] Investigative measures include various forensics actions and counter intelligence operations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Data loss incidents (unauthorized disclosure or deletion of sensitive data) may turn into data leak incidents (data breaches) when media containing sensitive information are lost and then acquired by an unauthorized party, including via data theft.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] However, a data leak is possible without losing the data on the originating side.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] There are limitations to the effectiveness of DLP systems in reducing risk of data loss.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Technological means for prevention data loss include standard security measures, advanced/intelligent security measures, access control and encryption, and content-aware DLP systems, although only the latter category is typically referred to as DLP.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Most DLP systems rely on predefined rules to identify and categorize sensitive information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Standard security measures, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDSs), and antivirus software, are widely used to guard against both outsider and insider attacks.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Intrusion detection systems identify unauthorized use, misuse, and abuse of computer systems by monitoring for behavior patterns that differ from legitimate users.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Advanced security measures employ machine learning, behavioral analytics, honeypots, temporal reasoning, and activity-based verification to detect abnormal or unauthorized data access patterns.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Machine learning algorithms enable systems to automatically improve through experience, identifying patterns in large datasets to enhance detection capabilities.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Content-aware DLP systems detect and prevent unauthorized attempts to copy, transmit, or publish sensitive data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems use mechanisms such as exact data matching, structured data fingerprinting, statistical methods, rule-based detection, and contextual analysis.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Network (data in motion) systems operate at egress points and analyze traffic for sensitive information being transmitted in violation of policy.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Next-generation firewalls and intrusion detection systems often support DLP-like capabilities.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Endpoint (data in use) systems monitor user actions on desktops, servers, and devices, enabling controls such as blocking copying, printing, screen capture, or unauthorized email transmission.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud DLP monitors data within cloud services and applies controls to enforce access and usage policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud computing provides on-demand network access to shared computing resources, enabling scalable and flexible data protection strategies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems help maintain compatibility with existing on-premises DLP infrastructure while addressing issues that are unique to cloud environments such as shared responsibility models, multi-cloud data governance, and shadow IT discovery.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Data identification techniques classify information as structured or unstructured.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Roughly 80% of enterprise data is unstructured.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Recent industry guidance describes data classification and policy alignment as foundational elements of effective DLP programs.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Vendors also emphasize the role of integrated DLP, analytics, and automation in modern data protection strategies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Data distributors may intentionally or unintentionally share data with third parties, after which it is later found in unauthorized locations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP investigations attempt to determine the source.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP techniques include access controls, encryption, and data retention policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Data encryption transforms readable information into an unreadable format to protect confidentiality, ensuring only authorized parties with the proper decryption key can access the original data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in use" refers to data currently being accessed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems may monitor and flag unauthorized manipulation or transfer of such data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in motion" refers to data traveling across internal or external networks.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems monitor and control this flow.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] False positive management remains a significant issue.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Policies that are too broad tend to generate alerts that require manual review which may overwhelm security teams and reduce the overall effectiveness of DLP software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Privacy and compliance concerns can arise when an organization monitors employees.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Achieving data security in such situations requires a delicate balance between adequate monitoring and taking care that individual privacy rights are not infringed upon.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Evasion techniques exist including steganography, encryption, or manipulation of a file's format that can sometimes circumvent DLP detection methods and require continuous updating of detection software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] The complexity of DLP policy increases substantially in global organizations due to their greater size and operation in disparate jurisdictions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP software in these cases must often contend with more diverse regulatory requirements, a broader range of data types, and relatively complex business processes.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] This makes it challenging to achieve consistent enforcement across regions and departments.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/data-loss-prevention-software] Relevant information privacy laws include the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), HIPAA in the United States, and the California Consumer Privacy Act.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A **digital watermark** is a kind of marker covertly embedded in a noise-tolerant signal such as audio, video or image data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] It is typically used to identify ownership of the copyright of such a signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Digital watermarking is the process of hiding digital information in a carrier signal; the hidden information should, but does not need to, contain a relation to the carrier signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Digital watermarks may be used to verify the authenticity or integrity of the carrier signal or to show the identity of its owners.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] It is prominently used for tracing copyright infringements and for banknote authentication.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Like traditional physical watermarks, digital watermarks are often only perceptible under certain conditions, e.g. after using some algorithm.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] If a digital watermark distorts the carrier signal in a way that it becomes easily perceivable, it may be considered less effective depending on its purpose.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Traditional watermarks may be applied to visible media (like images or video), whereas in digital watermarking, the signal may be audio, pictures, video, texts or 3D models.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A signal may carry several different watermarks at the same time.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Unlike metadata that is added to the carrier signal, a digital watermark does not change the size of the carrier signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The needed properties of a digital watermark depend on the use case in which it is applied.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] For marking media files with copyright information, a digital watermark has to be rather robust against modifications that can be applied to the carrier signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Instead, if integrity has to be ensured, a fragile watermark would be applied.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Both steganography and digital watermarking employ steganographic techniques to embed data covertly in noisy signals.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] While steganography aims for imperceptibility to human senses, digital watermarking tries to control the robustness as top priority.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Since a digital copy of data is the same as the original, digital watermarking is a passive protection tool.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] It just marks data, but does not degrade it or control access to the data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] One application of digital watermarking is *source tracking*.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A watermark is embedded into a digital signal at each point of distribution.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] If a copy of the work is found later, then the watermark may be retrieved from the copy and the source of the distribution is known.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] This technique has reportedly been used to detect the source of illegally copied movies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Watermarks are identification marks produced during the paper-making process.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The first watermarks appeared in Italy during the 13th century, but their use rapidly spread across Europe.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] They were used as a means to identify the paper maker or the trade guild that manufactured the paper.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The marks were often created by a wire sewn onto the paper mold.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Watermarks continue to be used today as manufacturers' marks and to prevent forgery.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The term *digital watermark* was coined by Andrew Tirkel and Charles Osborne in December 1992.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The first successful embedding and extraction of a steganographic spread spectrum watermark was demonstrated in 1993 by Andrew Tirkel, Gerard Rankin, Ron Van Schyndel, Charles Osborne, and others.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The information to be embedded in a signal is called a digital watermark, although in some contexts the phrase digital watermark means the difference between the watermarked signal and the cover signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The signal where the watermark is to be embedded is called the *host* signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A watermarking system is usually divided into three distinct steps, embedding, attack, and detection.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] In embedding, an algorithm accepts the host and the data to be embedded, and produces a watermarked signal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Then the watermarked digital signal is transmitted or stored, usually transmitted to another person.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] If this person makes a modification, this is called an *attack* or *tampering*.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] While the modification may not be malicious, the term attack arises from copyright protection application, where third parties may attempt to remove the digital watermark through modification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] There are many possible modifications, for example, affine transformations, lossy compression (e.g.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] MPEG-2), resolution reduction, standards conversion (e.g.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] NTSC to PAL), cropping an image or video, or intentionally adding noise.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *robust* with respect to transformations if the embedded information may be detected reliably from the marked signal, even if degraded by severe or multiple transformations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Typical image degradations are JPEG compression, rotation, cropping, additive noise, and quantization.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] For video content, temporal modifications and MPEG compression often are added to this list.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *imperceptible* if the watermarked content is perceptually equivalent to the original, unwatermarked content.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] In general, it is easy to create either robust watermarks *or* imperceptible watermarks, but the creation of both robust *and* imperceptible watermarks has proven to be quite challenging.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Robust imperceptible watermarks have been proposed as a tool for the protection of digital content, e.g. for Compact Disc and DVD copy protection, such as an embedded *no-copy-allowed* flag in professional video content.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Digital watermarking techniques may be classified in several ways.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *fragile* if it fails to be detectable after the slightest modification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Fragile watermarks are commonly used for tamper detection (integrity proof).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Modifications to an original work that clearly are noticeable, commonly are not referred to as watermarks, but as generalized barcodes.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *semi-fragile* if it resists benign transformations, but fails detection after malignant transformations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Semi-fragile watermarks commonly are used to detect malignant transformations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *robust* if it resists a designated class of transformations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Robust watermarks may be used in copy protection applications to carry copy and no access control information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *imperceptible* if the original cover signal and the marked signal are perceptually indistinguishable.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermark is called *perceptible* if its presence in the marked signal is noticeable (e.g. digital on-screen graphics like a network logo, content bug, codes, opaque images).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] On videos and images, some are made transparent/translucent for convenience for consumers due to the fact that they block portion of the view; therefore degrading it.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] This should not be confused with *perceptual*, that is, watermarking which uses the limitations of human perception to be imperceptible.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermarking method is referred to as *spread-spectrum* if the marked signal is obtained by an additive modification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Spread-spectrum watermarks are known to be modestly robust, but also to have a low information capacity due to host interference.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermarking method is said to be of *quantization type* if the marked signal is obtained by quantization.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Quantization watermarks suffer from low robustness, but have a high information capacity due to rejection of host interference.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A digital watermarking method is referred to as *amplitude modulation* if the marked signal is embedded by additive modification which is similar to spread spectrum method, but is particularly embedded in the spatial domain.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] The evaluation of digital watermarking schemes may provide detailed information for a watermark designer or for end-users, therefore, different evaluation strategies exist.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Often used by a watermark designer is the evaluation of single properties to show, for example, an improvement.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Mostly, end-users are not interested in detailed information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] They want to know if a given digital watermarking algorithm may be used for their application scenario, and if so, which parameter sets seems to be the best.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Epson and Kodak have produced cameras with security features such as the Epson PhotoPC 3000Z and the Kodak DC-290.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Both cameras added irremovable features to the pictures which distorted the original image, making them unacceptable for some applications such as forensic evidence in court.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] According to Blythe and Fridrich, "[n]either camera can provide an undisputable proof of the image origin or its author".
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A secure digital camera (SDC) was proposed by Saraju Mohanty, et al. in 2003 and published in January 2004.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] This was not the first time this was proposed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Blythe and Fridrich also have worked on SDC in 2004 for a digital camera that would use lossless watermarking to embed a biometric identifier together with a cryptographic hash.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Digital watermarking for relational databases has emerged as a candidate solution to provide copyright protection, tamper detection, traitor tracing, and maintaining integrity of relational data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] Many watermarking techniques have been proposed in the literature to address these purposes.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/digital-watermarking] A survey of the current state-of-the-art and a classification of the different techniques according to their intent, the way they express the watermark, the cover type, granularity level, and verifiability was published in 2010 by Halder et al. in the *Journal of Universal Computer Science*.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] To standardize this discipline, academics and professionals collaborate to offer guidance, policies, and industry standards on passwords, antivirus software, firewalls, encryption software, legal liability, security awareness and training, and so forth.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This standardization may be further driven by a wide variety of laws and regulations that affect how data is accessed, processed, stored, transferred, and destroyed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] While paper-based business operations are still prevalent, requiring their own set of information security practices, enterprise digital initiatives are increasingly being emphasized, with information assurance dealt with by information technology (IT) security specialists.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] These specialists apply information security to technology (most often some form of computer system).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] IT security specialists are hired by major enterprise/establishment to keep company technology secure from malicious attacks seeking to acquire critical private information or gain control of the internal systems.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] There are many specialist roles in Information Security including securing networks and allied infrastructure, securing applications and databases, security testing, information systems auditing, business continuity planning, electronic record discovery, and digital forensics.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Information security standards are guidelines generally outlined in published materials that aim to protect a user's or an organization's cyber environment from threats.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This environment includes the users themselves, hardware such as devices and networks, software such as applications or services, and any information in storage or transit.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] These standards comprise security concepts, technologies, and guidelines to deal with an adverse event.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] They may also include assessment criteria and certification for organizations implementing a minimum level of security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] These standards are developed by various international and national bodies to prevent or mitigate cyber-attacks, ensure consistency among developers, and establish a minimum standard in industries susceptible to an attack.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The ISO/IEC 27000 family, published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), provides information about the guidelines and requirements for an Information Security Management System (ISMS).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) provides guidelines on evaluating and certifying the security of a system.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The IEC 62443 establishes security standards for automation and control systems.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Similarly, the ISO/SAE 21434, ETSI EN 303 645, and EN 18031 provide standards for road vehicles, the Internet of Things, and radio-based systems respectively.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework (NIST CSF) is a set of guidelines developed by the U.S.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] National Institute of Standards and Technology to help organizations with risk management.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] NIST also publishes various Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) and Special Publications.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The United Kingdom has introduced Cyber Essentials, which is a certification scheme to protect organizations against common security threats.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The Australian Cyber Security Centre publishes the Essential Eight mitigation strategies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) regulates handling of cardholder data in order to reduce credit card fraud.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] UL has published standards related to specific industries such as UL 2900-2-3 for security and life safety signaling systems and UL-2900-2-1 for healthcare and wellness systems.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Information security threats come in many different forms.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Some of the most common threats today are software attacks, theft of intellectual property, theft of identity, theft of equipment or information, sabotage, and information extortion.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Viruses, worms, phishing attacks, and Trojan horses are a few common examples of software attacks.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The theft of intellectual property has also been an extensive issue for many businesses.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Identity theft is the attempt to act as someone else usually to obtain that person's personal information or to take advantage of their access to vital information through social engineering.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Sabotage usually consists of the destruction of an organization's website in an attempt to cause loss of confidence on the part of its customers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Information extortion consists of theft of a company's property or information as an attempt to receive a payment in exchange for returning the information or property back to its owner, as with ransomware.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] One of the most functional precautions against these attacks is to conduct periodical user awareness.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Governments, military, corporations, financial institutions, hospitals, non-profit organizations, and private businesses amass a great deal of confidential information about their employees, customers, products, research, and financial status.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Should confidential information about a business's customers or finances or new product line fall into the hands of a competitor or hacker, a business and its customers could suffer widespread, irreparable financial loss, as well as damage to the company's reputation.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] From a business perspective, information security must be balanced against cost; the Gordon-Loeb Model provides a mathematical economic approach for addressing this concern.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] For the individual, information security has a significant effect on privacy, which is viewed very differently in various cultures.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Since the early days of communication, diplomats and military commanders understood that it was necessary to provide some mechanism to protect the confidentiality of correspondence and to have some means of detecting tampering.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Julius Caesar is credited with the invention of the Caesar cipher c.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] 50 B.C., which was created in order to prevent his secret messages from being read should a message fall into the wrong hands.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] However, for the most part protection was achieved through the application of procedural handling controls.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Sensitive information was marked up to indicate that it should be protected and transported by trusted persons, guarded and stored in a secure environment or strong box.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] As postal services expanded, governments created official organizations to intercept, decipher, read, and reseal letters (e.g., the U.K.'s Secret Office, founded in 1653).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In the mid-nineteenth century more complex classification systems were developed to allow governments to manage their information according to the degree of sensitivity.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] For example, the British Government codified this, to some extent, with the publication of the Official Secrets Act in 1889.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Section 1 of the law concerned espionage and unlawful disclosures of information, while Section 2 dealt with breaches of official trust.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A public interest defense was soon added to defend disclosures in the interest of the state.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A similar law was passed in India in 1889, The Indian Official Secrets Act, which was associated with the British colonial era and used to crack down on newspapers that opposed the Raj's policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A newer version was passed in 1923 that extended to all matters of confidential or secret information for governance.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] By the time of the First World War, multi-tier classification systems were used to communicate information to and from various fronts, which encouraged greater use of code making and breaking sections in diplomatic and military headquarters.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Encoding became more sophisticated between the wars as machines were employed to scramble and unscramble information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The establishment of computer security inaugurated the history of information security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The need for such appeared during World War II.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The volume of information shared by the Allied countries during the Second World War necessitated formal alignment of classification systems and procedural controls.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] An arcane range of markings evolved to indicate who could handle documents (usually officers rather than enlisted troops) and where they should be stored as increasingly complex safes and storage facilities were developed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The Enigma Machine, which was employed by the Germans to encrypt the data of warfare and was successfully decrypted by Alan Turing, can be regarded as a striking example of creating and using secured information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Procedures evolved to ensure documents were destroyed properly, and it was the failure to follow these procedures which led to some of the greatest intelligence coups of the war (e.g., the capture of U-570).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Various mainframe computers were connected online during the Cold War to complete more sophisticated tasks, in a communication process easier than mailing magnetic tapes back and forth by computer centers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] As such, the Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA), of the United States Department of Defense, started researching the feasibility of a networked system of communication to trade information within the United States Armed Forces.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In 1968, the ARPANET project was formulated by Larry Roberts, which would later evolve into what is known as the internet.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Hackers had effortless access to ARPANET, as phone numbers were known by the public.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Due to these problems, coupled with the constant violation of computer security, as well as the exponential increase in the number of hosts and users of the system, "network security" was often alluded to as "network insecurity".
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The end of the twentieth century and the early years of the twenty-first century saw rapid advancements in telecommunications, computing hardware and software, and data encryption.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The availability of smaller, more powerful, and less expensive computing equipment made electronic data processing within the reach of small business and home users.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The establishment of Transfer Control Protocol/Internetwork Protocol (TCP/IP) in the early 1980s enabled different types of computers to communicate.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] These computers quickly became interconnected through the internet.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The rapid growth and widespread use of electronic data processing and electronic business conducted through the internet, along with numerous occurrences of international terrorism, fueled the need for better methods of protecting the computers and the information they store, process, and transmit.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The academic disciplines of computer security and information assurance emerged along with numerous professional organizations, all sharing the common goals of ensuring the security and reliability of information systems.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The "CIA triad" of ***c**onfidentiality, **i**ntegrity, and **a**vailability* is at the heart of information security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The concept was introduced in the Anderson Report in 1972 and later repeated in *The Protection of Information in Computer Systems.* The abbreviation was coined by Steve Lipner around 1986.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In information security, confidentiality "is the property, that information is not made available or disclosed to unauthorized individuals, entities, or processes." While similar to "privacy", the two words are not interchangeable.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Rather, confidentiality is a component of privacy that is implemented to protect data from unauthorized viewers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Examples of confidentiality of electronic data being compromised include laptop theft, password theft, or sensitive emails being sent to the incorrect individuals.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In IT security, data integrity means maintaining and assuring the accuracy and completeness of data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This means that data cannot be modified in an unauthorized or undetected manner.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] More broadly, integrity is an information security principle that involves human/social, process, and commercial integrity, as well as data integrity.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] As such it touches on aspects such as credibility, consistency, truthfulness, completeness, accuracy, timeliness, and assurance.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] For any information system to serve its purpose, the information must be available when it is needed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This means the computing systems used to store and process the information, the security controls used to protect it, and the communication channels used to access it must be functioning correctly.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Ensuring availability may also involve preventing denial-of-service attacks, such as a flood of incoming messages to the target system, essentially forcing it to shut down.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In addition to the classic CIA triad of security goals, some organisations may want to include security goals such as authenticity, accountability, non-repudiation, and reliability.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The merits of the Parkerian Hexad are a subject of debate amongst security professionals.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Risk is the likelihood that something bad will happen that causes harm to an informational asset (or the loss of the asset).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A vulnerability is a weakness that could be used to endanger or cause harm to an informational asset.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A threat is anything (man-made or act of nature) that has the potential to cause harm.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The likelihood that a threat will use a vulnerability to cause harm creates a risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] When a threat does use a vulnerability to inflict harm, it has an impact.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In the context of information security, the impact is a loss of availability, integrity, and confidentiality, and possibly other losses (lost income, loss of life, loss of real property).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] There are two things in this definition that may need some clarification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] First, the *process* of risk management is an ongoing, iterative process.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The business environment is constantly changing and new threats and vulnerabilities emerge every day.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Second, the choice of countermeasures (controls) used to manage risks must strike a balance between productivity, cost, effectiveness of the countermeasure, and the value of the informational asset being protected.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Furthermore, these processes have limitations as security breaches are generally rare and emerge in a specific context which may not be easily duplicated.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Thus, any process and countermeasure should itself be evaluated for vulnerabilities.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] It is not possible to identify all risks, nor is it possible to eliminate all risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The remaining risk is called "residual risk".
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A risk assessment is carried out by a team of people who have knowledge of specific areas of the business.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Membership of the team may vary over time as different parts of the business are assessed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The assessment may use a subjective qualitative analysis based on informed opinion, or where reliable dollar figures and historical information is available, the analysis may use quantitative analysis.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Research has shown that the most vulnerable point in most information systems is the human user, operator, designer, or other human.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Include: Acts of nature, acts of war, accidents, malicious acts originating from inside or outside the organization.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Conduct a vulnerability assessment, and for each vulnerability, calculate the probability that it will be exploited.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Evaluate policies, procedures, standards, training, physical security, quality control, technical security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Calculate the impact that each threat would have on each asset.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Use qualitative analysis or quantitative analysis.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Identify, select and implement appropriate controls.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Consider productivity, cost effectiveness, and value of the asset.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Evaluate the effectiveness of the control measures.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Ensure the controls provide the required cost effective protection without discernible loss of productivity.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] For any given risk, management can choose to accept the risk based upon the relative low value of the asset, the relative low frequency of occurrence, and the relative low impact on the business.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Or, leadership may choose to mitigate the risk by selecting and implementing appropriate control measures to reduce the risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In some cases, the risk can be transferred to another business by buying insurance or outsourcing to another business.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The reality of some risks may be disputed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In such cases leadership may choose to deny the risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Selecting and implementing proper security controls will initially help an organization bring down risk to acceptable levels.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Control selection should follow and should be based on the risk assessment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Controls can vary in nature, but fundamentally they are ways of protecting the confidentiality, integrity or availability of information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] ISO/IEC 27001 has defined controls in different areas.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Organizations can implement additional controls according to requirement of the organization.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] ISO/IEC 27002 offers a guideline for organizational information security standards.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Defense in depth is a fundamental security philosophy that relies on overlapping security systems designed to maintain protection even if individual components fail.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Rather than depending on a single security measure, it combines multiple layers of security controls both in the cloud and at network endpoints.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This approach includes combinations like firewalls with intrusion-detection systems, email filtering services with desktop anti-virus, and cloud-based security alongside traditional network defenses.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The concept can be implemented through three distinct layers of administrative, logical, and physical controls, or visualized as an onion model with data at the core, surrounded by people, network security, host-based security, and application security layers.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The strategy emphasizes that security involves not just technology, but also people and processes working together, with real-time monitoring and response being crucial components.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] An important aspect of information security and risk management is recognizing the value of information and defining appropriate procedures and protection requirements for the information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Not all information is equal and so not all information requires the same degree of protection.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This requires information to be assigned a security classification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The first step in information classification is to identify a member of senior management as the owner of the particular information to be classified.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The policy should describe the different classification labels, define the criteria for information to be assigned a particular label, and list the required security controls for each classification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Some factors that influence which classification information should be assigned include how much value that information has to the organization, how old the information is and whether or not the information has become obsolete.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Laws and other regulatory requirements are also important considerations when classifying information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] All employees in the organization, as well as business partners, must be trained on the classification schema and understand the required security controls and handling procedures for each classification.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Access to protected information must be restricted to people who are authorized to access the information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The computer programs, and in many cases the computers that process the information, must also be authorized.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This requires that mechanisms be in place to control the access to protected information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The sophistication of the access control mechanisms should be in parity with the value of the information being protected; the more sensitive or valuable the information the stronger the control mechanisms need to be.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The foundation on which access control mechanisms are built start with identification and authentication.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Access control is generally considered in three steps: identification, authentication, and authorization.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Identification is an assertion of who someone is or what something is.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] If a person makes the statement "Hello, my name is John Doe" they are making a claim of who they are.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] However, their claim may or may not be true.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Before John Doe can be granted access to protected information it will be necessary to verify that the person claiming to be John Doe really is John Doe.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Typically the claim is in the form of a username.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] By entering that username, John Doe is claiming that they are the person to whom the username belongs.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Authentication is the act of verifying a claim of identity.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] When John Doe goes into a bank to make a withdrawal, he tells the bank teller he is John Doe, a claim of identity.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The bank teller asks to see a photo ID, so he hands the teller his driver's license.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The bank teller checks the license to make sure it has John Doe printed on it and compares the photograph on the license against the person claiming to be John Doe.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] If the photo and name match the person, then the teller has authenticated that John Doe is who he claimed to be.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Similarly, by entering the correct password, the user is providing evidence that he/she is the person the username belongs to.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Strong authentication requires providing more than one type of authentication information (two-factor authentication).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The username is the most common form of identification on computer systems today and the password is the most common form of authentication.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Usernames and passwords have served their purpose, but they are increasingly inadequate.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Usernames and passwords are slowly being replaced or supplemented with more sophisticated authentication mechanisms such as time-based one-time password algorithms.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] After a person, program or computer has successfully been identified and authenticated then it must be determined what informational resources they are permitted to access and what actions they will be allowed to perform (run, view, create, delete, or change).
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Authorization to access information and other computing services begins with administrative policies and procedures.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The policies prescribe what information and computing services can be accessed, by whom, and under what conditions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The access control mechanisms are then configured to enforce these policies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Different computing systems are equipped with different kinds of access control mechanisms.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Some may even offer a choice of different access control mechanisms.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The access control mechanism a system offers will be based upon one of three approaches to access control, or it may be derived from a combination of the three approaches.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The non-discretionary approach consolidates all access control under a centralized administration.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The access to information and other resources is usually based on the individuals function (role) in the organization or the tasks the individual must perform.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The discretionary approach gives the creator or owner of the information resource the ability to control access to those resources.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] In the mandatory access control approach, access is granted or denied basing upon the security classification assigned to the information resource.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] To be effective, policies and other security controls must be enforceable and upheld.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Effective policies ensure that people are held accountable for their actions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Treasury's guidelines for systems processing sensitive or proprietary information, for example, states that all failed and successful authentication and access attempts must be logged, and all access to information must leave some type of audit trail.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Also, the need-to-know principle needs to be in effect when talking about access control.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This principle gives access rights to a person to perform their job functions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This principle is used in the government when dealing with difference clearances.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Even though two employees in different departments have a top-secret clearance, they must have a need-to-know in order for information to be exchanged.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Within the need-to-know principle, network administrators grant the employee the least amount of privilege to prevent employees from accessing more than what they are supposed to.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Need-to-know helps to enforce the confidentiality-integrity-availability triad and directly impacts the confidential area of the triad.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Information security uses cryptography to transform usable information into a form that renders it unusable by anyone other than an authorized user; this process is called encryption.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Information that has been encrypted (rendered unusable) can be transformed back into its original usable form by an authorized user who possesses the cryptographic key, through the process of decryption.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Cryptography is used in information security to protect information from unauthorized or accidental disclosure while the information is in transit (either electronically or physically) and while information is in storage.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Cryptography provides information security with other useful applications as well, including improved authentication methods, message digests, digital signatures, non-repudiation, and encrypted network communications.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Older, less secure applications such as Telnet and File Transfer Protocol (FTP) are slowly being replaced with more secure applications such as Secure Shell (SSH) that use encrypted network communications.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Wireless communications can be encrypted using protocols such as WPA/WPA2 or the older (and less secure) WEP.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Wired communications (such as ITU‑T G.hn) are secured using AES for encryption and X.1035 for authentication and key exchange.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Software applications such as GnuPG or PGP can be used to encrypt data files and email.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Cryptography can introduce security problems when it is not implemented correctly.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Cryptographic solutions need to be implemented using industry-accepted solutions that have undergone rigorous peer review by independent experts in cryptography.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The length and strength of the encryption key is also an important consideration.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A key that is weak or too short will produce weak encryption.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The keys used for encryption and decryption must be protected with the same degree of rigor as any other confidential information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] They must be protected from unauthorized disclosure and destruction, and they must be available when needed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Public key infrastructure (PKI) solutions address many of the problems that surround key management.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Federal Sentencing Guidelines now make it possible to hold corporate officers liable for failing to exercise due care and due diligence in the management of their information systems.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Attention should be made to two important points in these definitions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] First, in due care, steps are taken to show; this means that the steps can be verified, measured, or even produce tangible artifacts.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Second, in due diligence, there are continual activities; this means that people are actually doing things to monitor and maintain the protection mechanisms, and these activities are ongoing.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Organizations have a responsibility with practicing duty of care when applying information security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The Duty of Care Risk Analysis Standard (DoCRA) provides principles and practices for evaluating risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] It considers all parties that could be affected by those risks.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] DoCRA helps evaluate safeguards if they are appropriate in protecting others from harm while presenting a reasonable burden.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] With increased data breach litigation, companies must balance security controls, compliance, and its mission.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Computer security incident management is a specialized form of incident management focused on monitoring, detecting, and responding to security events on computers and networks in a predictable way.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Organizations implement this through incident response plans (IRPs) that are activated when security breaches are detected.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] These plans typically involve an incident response team (IRT) with specialized skills in areas like penetration testing, computer forensics, and network security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Change management is a formal process for directing and controlling alterations to the information processing environment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This includes alterations to desktop computers, the network, servers, and software.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The objectives of change management are to reduce the risks posed by changes to the information processing environment and improve the stability and reliability of the processing environment as changes are made.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] It is not the objective of change management to prevent or hinder necessary changes from being implemented.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Any change to the information processing environment introduces an element of risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Even apparently simple changes can have unexpected effects.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] One of management's many responsibilities is the management of risk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Change management is a tool for managing the risks introduced by changes to the information processing environment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Part of the change management process ensures that changes are not implemented at inopportune times when they may disrupt critical business processes or interfere with other changes being implemented.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Some kinds of changes are a part of the everyday routine of information processing and adhere to a predefined procedure, which reduces the overall level of risk to the processing environment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Creating a new user account or deploying a new desktop computer are examples of changes that do not generally require change management.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] However, relocating user file shares, or upgrading the Email server pose a much higher level of risk to the processing environment and are not a normal everyday activity.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The critical first steps in change management are (a) defining change (and communicating that definition) and (b) defining the scope of the change system.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Change management is usually overseen by a change review board composed of representatives from key business areas, security, networking, systems administrators, database administration, application developers, desktop support, and the help desk.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The tasks of the change review board can be facilitated with the use of automated work flow application.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The responsibility of the change review board is to ensure the organization's documented change management procedures are followed.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Change management procedures that are simple to follow and easy to use can greatly reduce the overall risks created when changes are made to the information processing environment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Good change management procedures improve the overall quality and success of changes as they are implemented.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] This is accomplished through planning, peer review, documentation, and communication.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] ISO/IEC 20000, The Visible OPS Handbook: Implementing ITIL in 4 Practical and Auditable Steps (Full book summary), and ITIL all provide valuable guidance on implementing an efficient and effective change management program information security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Business continuity management (BCM) concerns arrangements aiming to protect an organization's critical business functions from interruption due to incidents, or at least minimize the effects.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] BCM is essential to any organization to keep technology and business in line with current threats to the continuation of business as usual.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] The BCM should be included in an organizations risk analysis plan to ensure that all of the necessary business functions have what they need to keep going in the event of any type of threat to any business function.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Whereas BCM takes a broad approach to minimizing disaster-related risks by reducing both the probability and the severity of incidents, a disaster recovery plan (DRP) focuses specifically on resuming business operations as quickly as possible after a disaster.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] A disaster recovery plan, invoked soon after a disaster occurs, lays out the steps necessary to recover critical information and communications technology (ICT) infrastructure.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Disaster recovery planning includes establishing a planning group, performing risk assessment, establishing priorities, developing recovery strategies, preparing inventories and documentation of the plan, developing verification criteria and procedure, and lastly implementing the plan.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Below is a partial listing of governmental laws and regulations in various parts of the world that have, had, or will have, a significant effect on data processing and information security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Important industry sector regulations have also been included when they have a significant impact on information security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p01] Andersson and Reimers (2019) report these certifications range from CompTIA's A+ and Security+ through the ICS2.org's CISSP, etc.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p02] Describing more than simply how security aware employees are, information security culture is the ideas, customs, and social behaviors of an organization that impact information security in both positive and negative ways.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p02] Cultural concepts can help different segments of the organization work effectively or work against effectiveness towards information security within an organization.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p02] The way employees think and feel about security and the actions they take can have a big impact on information security in organizations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p02] Andersson and Reimers (2014) found that employees often do not see themselves as part of the organization Information Security "effort" and often take actions that ignore organizational information security best interests.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-security-p02] Research shows information security culture needs to be improved continuously.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] This refers to information that is already a matter of public record or knowledge.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] With regard to government and private organizations, access to or release of such information may be requested by any member of the public, and there are often formal processes laid out for how to do so.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The accessibility of government-held public records is an important part of government transparency, accountability to its citizens, and the values of democracy.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Public records may furthermore refer to information about identifiable individuals that is not considered confidential, including but not limited to: census records, criminal records, sex offender registry files, and voter registration.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] This includes business information that is not subjected to special protection and may be routinely shared with anyone inside or outside of the business.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] However, there are situations in which the release of personal information could have a negative effect on its owner.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] For example, a person trying to avoid a stalker will be inclined to further restrict access to such personal information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Furthermore, a person's SSN or SIN, credit card numbers, and other financial information may be considered private if their disclosure might lead to crimes such as identity theft or fraud.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Some types of private information, including records of a person's health care, education, and employment may be protected by privacy laws.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Unauthorized disclosure of private information can make the perpetrator liable for civil remedies and may in some cases be subject to criminal penalties.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Even though they are often used interchangeably, personal information is sometimes distinguished from private information, or personally identifiable information.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The latter is distinct from the former in that Private information can be used to identify a unique individual.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Personal information, on the other hand, is information belonging to the private life of an individual that cannot be used to uniquely identify that individual.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] This can range from an individual's favourite colour, to the details of their domestic life.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The latter is a common example of personal information that is also regarded as sensitive, where the individual sharing these details with a trusted listener would prefer for it not to be shared with anyone else, and the sharing of which may result in unwanted consequences.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Confidential business information (CBI) refers to information whose disclosure may harm the business.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Such information may include trade secrets, sales and marketing plans, new product plans, notes associated with patentable inventions, customer and supplier information, financial data, and more.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Under TSCA, CBI is defined as proprietary information, considered confidential to the submitter, the release of which would cause substantial business injury to the owner.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The US EPA may as of 2016, review and determine if a company´s claim is valid.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Classified information generally refers to information that is subject to special security classification regulations imposed by many national governments, the disclosure of which may cause harm to national interests and security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The protocol of restriction imposed upon such information is categorized into a hierarchy of classification levels in almost every national government worldwide, with the most restricted levels containing information that may cause the greatest danger to national security if leaked.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Authorized access is granted to individuals on a need to know basis who have also passed the appropriate level of security clearance.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Classified information can be reclassified to a different level or declassified (made available to the public) depending on changes of situation or new intelligence.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Classified information may also be further denoted with the method of communication or access.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] For example, Protectively Marked "Secret" Eyes Only or Protectively Marked "Secret" Encrypted transfer only.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Indicating that the document must be physically read by the recipient and cannot be openly discussed for example over a telephone conversation or that the communication can be sent only using encrypted means.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Often mistakenly listed as meaning for the eyes of the intended recipient only the anomaly becomes apparent when the additional tag "Not within windowed area" is also used.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Data privacy concerns exist in various aspects of daily life wherever personal data is stored and collected, such as on the internet, in medical records, financial records, and expression of political opinions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] In over 80 countries in the world, personally identifiable information is protected by information privacy laws, which outline limits to the collection and use of personally identifiable information by public and private entities.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Such laws usually require entities to give clear and unambiguous notice to the individual of the types of data being collected, its reason for collection, and planned uses of the data.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] In consent-based legal frameworks, explicit consent of the individual is required as well.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The European Union passed the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), replacing the earlier Data Protection Directive.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The regulation was adopted on 27 April 2016.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] It became enforceable from 25 May 2018 after a two-year transition period and, unlike a directive, it does not require national governments to pass any enabling legislation, and is thus directly binding and applicable.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] "The proposed new EU data protection regime extends the scope of the EU data protection law to all foreign companies processing data of EU residents.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] In Canada, the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) regulates the collection and use of personal data and electronic documents by public and private organizations.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] PIPEDA is in effect in all federal and provincial jurisdictions, except provinces where existing privacy laws are determined to be “substantially similar”.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Whether being regulated or self regulated, the laws require to establish ways at which access to sensitive information is limited to the people with different roles, thus in essence requiring establishment of the "sensitive data domain" model and mechanisms of its protection.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Some of the domains have a guideline in form of pre-defined models such as "Safe Harbor" of HIPAA, based on the research of Latanya Sweeny and established privacy industry metrics.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Additionally, many other countries have enacted their own legislature regarding data privacy protection, and more are still in the process of doing so.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The confidentiality of sensitive business information is established through non-disclosure agreements, a legally binding contract between two parties in a professional relationship.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] NDAs may be one-way, such as in the case of an employee receiving confidential information about the employing organization, or two-way between businesses needing to share information with one another to accomplish a business goal.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Depending on the severity of consequences, a violation of non-disclosure may result in employment loss, loss of business and client contacts, criminal charges or a civil lawsuit, and a hefty sum in damages.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Unlike personal and private information, there is no internationally recognized framework protecting trade secrets, or even an agreed-upon definition of the term “trade secret”.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] However, many countries and political jurisdictions have taken the initiative to account for the violation of commercial confidentiality in their criminal or civil laws.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] For example, under the US Economic Espionage Act of 1996, it is a federal crime in the United States to misappropriate trade secrets with the knowledge that it will benefit a foreign power, or will injure the owner of the trade secret.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] More commonly, breach of commercial confidentiality falls under civil law, such as in the United Kingdom.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] In some developing countries, trade secret laws are either non-existent or poorly developed and offer little substantial protection.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] In many countries, unauthorized disclosure of classified information is a criminal offence, and may be punishable by fines, prison sentence, or even the death penalty, depending on the severity of the violation.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] For less severe violations, civil sanctions may be imposed, ranging from reprimand to revoking of security clearance and subsequent termination of employment.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Whistleblowing is the intentional disclosure of sensitive information to a third-party with the intention of revealing alleged illegal, immoral, or otherwise harmful actions.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] There are many examples of present and former government employees disclosing classified information regarding national government misconduct to the public and media, in spite of the criminal consequences that await them.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Espionage, or spying, involves obtaining sensitive information without the permission or knowledge of its holder.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The use of spies is a part of national intelligence gathering in most countries, and has been used as a political strategy by nation-states since ancient times.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] It is unspoken knowledge in international politics that countries are spying on one another all the time, even their allies.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Computer security is information security applied to computing and network technology, and is a significant and ever-growing field in computer science.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The term computer insecurity, on the other hand, is the concept that computer systems are inherently vulnerable to attack, and therefore an evolving arms race between those who exploit existing vulnerabilities in security systems and those who must then engineer new mechanisms of security.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] A number of security concerns have arisen in the recent years as increasing amounts of sensitive information at every level have found their primary existence in digital form.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] At the personal level, credit card fraud, internet fraud, and other forms of identity theft have become widespread concerns that individuals need to be aware of on a day-to-day basis.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The existence of large databases of classified information on computer networks is also changing the face of domestic and international politics.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Cyber-warfare and cyber espionage is becoming of increasing importance to the national security and strategy of nations around the world, and it is estimated that 120 nations around the world are currently actively engaged in developing and deploying technology for these purposes.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] Philosophies and internet cultures such as open-source governance, hacktivism, and the popular hacktivist slogan "information wants to be free" reflects some of the cultural shifts in perception towards political and government secrecy.
[src:data-loss-prevention-deep/information-sensitivity] The popular, controversial WikiLeaks is just one of many manifestations of a growing cultural sentiment that is becoming an additional challenge to the security and integrity of classified information.
